In this article, President Joseph R. Biden Jr. reflects on Memorial Day and honors the courage, integrity, and selfless dedication of the members of the Armed Forces who have made the ultimate sacrifice in service to the nation. He acknowledges the sacrifices made by American service members in various conflicts around the world and highlights their embodiment of the American spirit. The President emphasizes the debt owed to fallen heroes and their families, expressing solidarity as he and his wife understand the concern for loved ones serving in war zones. He emphasizes the sacred obligation to support Gold Star families and honor the memories of their loved ones. President Biden pledges to uphold the values for which these fallen service members fought and to work towards equity and inclusion in the country and its institutions. He expresses gratitude to the current and past members of the Armed Services and their contributions to forging a legacy of peace. The President issues a proclamation designating Memorial Day as a day of prayer for permanent peace and calls for a National Moment of Remembrance at 3:00 p.m. local time. He requests that flags be flown at half-staff until noon and encourages the public to display flags at half-staff from their homes. The article concludes with President Biden's signature and the date of the proclamation.